english:
  title: Preface to the Revised and Annotated Edition of the Six Administrative Codes
  author: Gwon Chae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Just as heaven requires the four seasons and humanity requires the five virtues, so too must a nation possess the Six Administrative Codes—without them, governance cannot be achieved. Thus, whenever sage kings arise, they establish the proper institutions, and their wisdom is transmitted to posterity through the records they leave behind.

    The governance of Yao and Shun was inscribed in the Classic of Documents, and the statecraft of Kings Wen and Wu was preserved in the canonical texts. From the official histories of Qin and Han through the compilations of Tang and Song, we can observe how institutions evolve through both preservation and transformation. Yet in our Eastern realm, as the previous dynasty declined, the systems fell into disrepair, and we nearly lost all trace of these ancient records.

    When our Great Founder, King Taejo, received the Mandate of Heaven and renewed the institutions, his grand vision transcended a thousand ages. At that time, the esteemed Minister Cho Jun and others, fearing these laws might be lost to time, gathered the ordinances and regulations established since the founding of our dynasty, organized them systematically, and modeled them after the Six Officials of the Zhou—thus creating the legal framework for our sage dynasty. These founding principles and models for our descendants were thereby preserved in full.

    Though these writings prioritized comprehensiveness, they were composed in varied language and dialect. During the reign of our sovereign Lord Taejong, Minister Ha Ryun and others refined this work by removing the colloquialisms and polishing the prose, naming it the Revised and Annotated Edition of the Six Administrative Codes. A supplementary volume was added, expanding the sections considerably. Yet certain passages differed from the original text and were revised accordingly. In the year Eulmi, the Ministry of Rites was commanded to review and verify the entire work, restoring it to its original form where possible. Where circumstances or changing times necessitated retention of revisions, these were noted in annotations below the original passages—thus preserving both fidelity to the ancient precedents and flexibility to accommodate the needs of each era.

    Yet over time, redundancies accumulated, and since the year Munja, certain provisions have conflicted with or duplicated earlier ones, causing difficulty for those charged with administering them. Our Sovereign Lord, moved by deep concern, has now commanded Minister Lee Jik and others to undertake a comprehensive revision. Following strictly the original text, they have removed contradictions, eliminated duplications, and where the times require modifications, these are carefully annotated—much like water flowing from source to estuary, or a room properly finished and plastered. Each element connects to what precedes and follows, whether great or small, all is included and complete. Those who study this will see it as clearly as looking into their own palm; those who administer it will find precise guidance in every article. Thus is the original intent of these codes made luminous anew.

    In the seventh month of the year Byeongno of the Xuande era, the compilation was completed, transcribed, and presented. By imperial command it was printed and distributed for perpetual observance. I was further commanded to compose this preface explaining its genesis.

    Humbly reflecting upon this matter, I recall that since ancient times, when sage emperors and wise kings established their dynasties and preserved their achievements, they necessarily created comprehensive and flawless institutions to secure the welfare of their posterity, and established the means of respectful transmission and worthy continuance to honor their ancestors' legacies. Observing our royal lineage, I see how the founders established laws and principles on so grand a scale, and how our Sovereign, continuing their vision and building upon their works, has brought forth such refined and detailed governance. When the ministers worked together in harmonious cooperation to refine and perfect this Great Code, it truly became worthy to stand alongside the Classic of Documents of Yao's age and the institutional framework of Zhou—both reflecting the same fundamental principles and sharing equal beauty.

    When these Six Codes are put into practice, all worthy accomplishments shall be achieved. Good governance shall flourish above, and the people shall cooperate below. Thus shall the eternal enterprise endure through ten thousand ages without end—and this depends upon what is contained herein.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Six Administrative Codes' (육전) are modeled on the Six Officials (육관) of the Zhou dynasty, representing the fundamental administrative structure of Joseon.
  - key: ''
    value: Cho Jun (趙浚) was a key architect of Joseon's early institutional framework under Taejo.
  - key: ''
    value: Ha Ryun (河崙) served as Left Minister under Taejong and was responsible for refining and standardizing administrative codes.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'year Eulmi' refers to 1415, when a comprehensive review and standardization of the codes was undertaken.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Jik (李稷) served as Left Minister and conducted the final comprehensive revision of the codes.
  - key: ''
    value: Xuande era (宣德) was a reign period of the Ming dynasty; the 'year Byeongno' (丙午) refers to 1426.
